|>    I suspect that many foreign intelligence services will succeed in getting
|> the algorithm back out, but I'd be quite surprised if someone published
|> Skipjack.  Certainly, doing so in the US would lead to some nasty
|> consequences.  And somehow, I don't think an anonymous remailer would keep
|> your identity secret from the FBI or NSA, if they were interested in looking
|> for you.
|>  
|>    Doesn't NSA have other classified encryption schemes, used for classified
|> military data?  How many of those have been published recently?  I'm sure
|> everyone on this list would be interested in seeing how recently-designed
|> algorithms from the NSA work, and trying to tease out of their structure
|> any information we can about what the NSA knows and we don't.
|>  
|>    --John Kelsey

John, my friend, look at the distribution of most of these notes.  They say 
"world" and it's a mighty big place.

Myself, I confidently expect to see Skipjack published in some Eurocrypt
proceedings or other in the next 4 or 5 years, especially if the darn thing
is actually produced in any volumes.  There is a decidely
different attitude in W. Europe towards this sort of thing.

It's mostly a question of economics.  Will someone, somewhere put out the
bucks to do a "tear down" of the chip and figure out how it works.  I could
imagine some crypto company in Europe doing just that and being also motivated
to publish what they find for competitive reasons. . . 

